&lt;p&gt;The outlet to the biogas system.  Manure goes in, methane comes out this pipe.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I got to visit the house of an Afghan doctor who has done his house up nicely.  He lives out in the countryside, where there are no utilities.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
He has a micro-hydro plant which grinds wheat on one side and provides electricity for 8 or 9 nearby families.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
He also has a biogas generator which uses anaroebic fermentation of manure to generate methane to cook and heat his house.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Micro_hydro" rel="nofollow"&gt;en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Micro_hydro&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
